definition.value: A 3,20-dioxo steroid having the structure of cortisol but lacking one or more of its hydroxy groups.
A deoxyhexose comprising glucose having at least one hydroxy group replaced by hydrogen.
Any C6 deoxy sugar having at least one hydroxy group replaced by hydrogen.
Any sugar having a hydroxy group replaced with a hydrogen atom.
A triterpenoid saponin that is (22S,24Z)-3beta-hydroxy-26-oxo-22,26-epoxy-9beta,19-cyclolanost-24-en-28-oic acid having a beta-D-glucosyl residue attached at position 3 via a glycosidic bond.
A natural or synthetic compound having a sequence of amino and hydroxy carboxylic acid residues (usually alpha-amino and alpha-hydroxy acids), commonly but not necessarily regularly alternating.

The naturally occurring (1'S)-(+) enantiomer of abscisic acid. It is an important sesquiterpenoid plant hormone which acts as a regulator of plant responses to environmental stresses such as drought and cold.
A dimeric sesquiterpene lactone that is produced by the plant Artemisia absinthium (Wormwood). The bitter tasting constituent of Absinthe.
Any polyamine that contains two amino groups.
A monohydroxyflavanone that is (2S)-2',2'-dimethyl-2,3-dihydro-2'H,4H-2,6'-bichromen-4-one carrying a hydroxy substituent at position 7.
A dicarboxylic acid dianion that is the conjugate base of 2,6-diaminopimelic acid.
The amino dicarboxylic acid that is heptanedioic acid with amino substituents at C-2 and C-6.
An azole that is either one of a pair of heterocyclic organic compounds comprising three carbon atoms and two nitrogen atoms arranged in a ring.
A trihydroxyflavanone that is flavanone substituted by hydroxy groups at positions 5, 7 and 4' and prenyl groups at positions 3' and 5' respectively.
A mancude organic heterotricyclic parent that consists of a thiophene ring flanked by two benzene rings ortho-fused across the 2,3- and 4,5-positions.
A member of the class of dibenzothiophenes that is the 5-oxo derivative of dibenzothiophene.
A bromobisphenol substituted by two bromo groups at unspecified positions.
A member of the class of chalcones that is isolated from the stem of Erythrina abyssinica.
Any member of the class of chlorobenzenes carrying two chloro groups at unspecified positions.
Any  chlorobenzoyl-CoA having dichlorobenzoyl as the aroyl substituent.
A chlorocatechol carrying two chloro groups at unspecified positions.
A member of the class of  chlorohydroquinones carrying two chloro substituents at unspecified positions.
Any chlorophenol carrying chloro substituents.
A monocarboxylic acid anion that is obtained by removal of a proton from the carboxylic acid group of difluoroacetic acid.
A monocarboxylic acid that is acetic acid in which two of the methyl hydrogens are substituted by fluorines.

A member of the class of tetrahydropyridines that is 2,3-dihydroxy-4-methoxy-1-methyl-6-oxo-1,2,3,6-tetrahydropyridine-3-carbonitrile having a beta-D-glucosyl residue attached at position 3 via a glycosidic bond.
A member of the class of 1-benzofurans that is 1-benzofuran-4,7-dione bearing additional methyl and methoxy substituents at positions 2 and 7 respectively.
An oxo monocarboxylic acid that is 2,5-dihydrofuran-2-ylacetic acid substituted by an oxo group at position 5.
A dihydrocarvone resulting from reduction of the endocyclic cyclohexene double bond.
A 3-oxo steroid that is cortisone in which the double bond between positions 4 and 5 has been reduced to a single bond.
